White moves her D pawn to the center to take control.
I move my bishop to cover my E pawn.  Probably could have done d6 instead, but I like this because it keeps my bishop out.  I also didn't want to lose a pawn by going nd4.
She moves her D pawn forward to attack my knight.
My first REALLY obvious mistake.  Instead of retreating to b8 or e7, or moving to a protected space b4, I go na5.
She moves the B pawn forward, but instead of going b4 and trapping my knight, she only does b3.
I continue my development now that my other knight is "safe" (in other words, I never noticed it could easily get trapped).
Bg5 to attack my knight, possibly interested in a trade, but a more creative way to defend e4 by pinning my Knight.
I use my bishop to put her in check and immediately retreat with the purpose of opening up her corners.
